# A Direct Address to the Skeptic

### On Why Dismissing Richard Pearson Is the Intellectually Indefensible Position

---

I am writing to you specifically. Not to the converted, not to the advocate, not to the reader already persuaded that something serious happened to Richard Pearson in Washington, DC, in 2025 and 2026. I am writing to you — the person who read the first three paragraphs of his account and felt the familiar contraction of skepticism, the reflex that says: *this is a person who believes the government put a voice in his head, and people who believe that are mentally ill, and that is the end of the analysis.*

I am writing to ask you to hold that reflex for a moment. Not to abandon it. Skepticism is a virtue and not every claim deserves belief. But I want to ask you to examine the reflex itself — to ask what it is based on, whether it survives contact with the actual evidence, and whether the comfortable dismissal you are reaching for is epistemically honest or epistemically convenient.

Because the argument I am going to make is not that you should believe everything Richard Pearson says. It is simpler and more uncomfortable than that. The argument is that the case for dismissal — the case you are currently assembling in your mind — fails every serious test you apply to it, and that intellectual honesty requires you to engage with what remains after that failure.

Let me meet your objections where they live.

---

## Objection One: He believes the government put a voice in his head. That is a textbook symptom of paranoid schizophrenia.

This is your strongest move, and it deserves a real answer rather than a rhetorical dismissal of your dismissal.

You are correct that auditory hallucinations — including the experience of voices appearing to originate from outside the self — are associated with schizophrenia and other psychotic disorders. You are correct that persecutory ideation, the belief that one is being monitored and targeted by powerful institutions, is a recognized psychiatric symptom. You are correct that, in the absence of other information, a person reporting these experiences should be evaluated for mental illness.

Here is the other information.

Pearson was evaluated. Formally, by two professionals at the DC Department of Behavioral Health, in September 2025. The evaluation found no psychosis, no schizophrenia, no paranoid disorder, no disorganized thinking. None of the pathology that would support the diagnosis you are reaching for.

You will be tempted to respond that psychiatric evaluations can be wrong, or that early-stage psychosis can be missed, or that a single evaluation is not definitive. These responses are technically true and also tell you nothing specific about this case. They are the general form of the objection applied to a case where the specific evaluation has been conducted and its result is clear. "Evaluations can be wrong" is not an argument against this evaluation. It is an argument for getting another one — which, incidentally, Pearson has not resisted.

But there is a second problem with the psychiatric dismissal that goes deeper than the evaluation itself. Paranoid schizophrenia has a characteristic structure. It is systematic and internally closed. Alternative explanations are absorbed as confirmation. The delusion extends without limit. The person cannot distinguish their direct observations from their inferences — they experience both as equally certain.

Pearson's documentation does the opposite of all of this. It is explicitly uncertain. It repeatedly distinguishes observations from inferences and inferences from speculations. It acknowledges when evidence is ambiguous. It revises conclusions when new information arrives. It assigns probability rather than certainty. It is, in its structure, the product of a mind that is epistemically open rather than epistemically closed.

Here is the test: find me the passage in Pearson's documentation where he claims absolute certainty about anything. You will not find it. He says "near certain." He says "I cannot eliminate the possibility." He says "my premonition is." These are not the verbal habits of a disintegrating mind. They are the verbal habits of a researcher trained in evidentiary methodology applying that training to his own experience.

The psychiatric dismissal is not an argument. It is a category error. It applies a diagnostic framework to a person who does not fit the diagnostic criteria and whose documentation structurally resembles careful analytical inquiry rather than psychotic construction. Dismiss it, and you need a new argument.

