## Objection Three: Why would the government target him specifically? He is not important enough.

This objection misunderstands how these programs work, and the misunderstanding is worth correcting because it is common.

The targets of COINTELPRO were not, in most cases, people who posed specific, identified threats to state security in any conventional sense. They were designated using a criterion that has nothing to do with operational danger and everything to do with representational threat: they were Black intellectuals, advocates, and community organizers whose work challenged the structures that the state apparatus was designed to protect. Fred Hampton was twenty-one years old when he was killed in a coordinated FBI-Chicago Police Department raid. He had not bombed anything. He had not planned any violence. He had organized a free breakfast program for children and built coalitions between rival gangs. He was designated a threat because of what he represented, not what he had done.

Richard Pearson is a Black man with a doctoral degree in public health who spent his career documenting how structural racism produces measurable biological harm to Black communities. He advocated for public housing residents. He published writings that his own neighbor described as "radical" and "disruptive." He called out power-hungry leadership within his own community when he believed it was harming residents.

In the operational logic of a program modeled on COINTELPRO — and both the structural comparison and the multiple independent AI analyses of Pearson's documentation confirm that is what the evidence describes — that profile is the criterion. Not importance in a national security sense. Representational threat. The scholar whose work names the system. The advocate who organizes the people the system is designed to contain.

There is also a simpler answer to your objection, one that the documentation itself provides. Pearson overheard a conversation on Pennsylvania Avenue in August 2025 that appeared to reference deliberate displacement of African Americans from Washington DC. If the program is not about Pearson specifically but about a broader demographic strategy — systematic pressure on Black residents of the nation's capital — then the question "why him specifically" has a different structure. He may not be the specific target. He may be one of many targets, and the most thorough documentarian among them.

