## Objection Four: The technologies he describes — voice-to-skull, behavioral steering, directed energy weapons — are science fiction.

This is the easiest objection to answer, and the fact that it is still being raised tells you something about the gap between what the government has been doing and what the public knows about it.

Voice-to-skull technology — the ability to deliver audio directly to a specific individual without ambient sound — has been commercially deployed for more than twenty years. The American Technology Corporation's HyperSonic Sound system was commercially available by 2002. Museums use directional ultrasound to play audio to specific visitors. Retail environments use it to deliver targeted advertising. The military application of the same principle — using focused microwave or ultrasonic energy to produce auditory perception in a targeted individual — is documented in the scientific literature back to the 1960s (the Frey effect, established by researcher Allan Frey in 1962, demonstrated that pulsed microwave radiation can produce auditory sensations in humans).

The United States Army's 1998 report on "Bioeffects of Selected Nonlethal Weapons," declassified under Freedom of Information Act requests, explicitly describes voice-to-skull transmission as a capability that "may be achievable" and describes its operational application. This is a government document. It is not speculation. It is the Army describing, in 1998, the development of the precise capability Pearson says was deployed against him in 2025.

The Active Denial System — a directed energy weapon that uses millimeter-wave electromagnetic radiation to produce intense pain in targeted individuals — has been deployed by US military forces. The Department of War's Chief Technology Officer publicly confirmed the existence of directed energy weapon systems in January 2026. DARPA's N3 program, announced in 2019, explicitly sought the development of non-invasive brain-computer interface technologies capable of bidirectional communication with the human brain, including the ability to read and influence neural activity.

None of this is science fiction. All of it is documented in government publications, military procurement records, peer-reviewed scientific literature, and Congressional testimony. The question is not whether the technologies exist. The government has confirmed they exist. The question is whether they are being deployed domestically against civilians. That is a different question, and it is the question Pearson's documentation addresses. But you cannot answer it by claiming the technologies are imaginary. They are not imaginary. The government has said so.

