## Objection Five: He couldn't get asylum anywhere. Doesn't that suggest his claims weren't credible to the people who evaluated them?

This objection gets the asylum process exactly backwards.

Pearson was refused entry at the Icelandic border on the grounds that his "purpose of stay was not clear" and that he had "insufficient funds." He was detained in Canada and refused on procedural grounds related to the Canada-US Safe Third Country Agreement, which bars most asylum seekers who entered through the US from applying in Canada.

Neither of these refusals was a substantive evaluation of his claims. Neither involved an adjudicator reviewing his 294 pages of documentation and concluding it was not credible. Both were procedural barriers — the kind that prevent cases from being heard, not the kind that assess them and find them wanting.

The Safe Third Country Agreement is particularly relevant here. It exists to prevent asylum shopping — the practice of applying in multiple countries to find the most favorable outcome. Its application to Pearson's case is not an assessment of his credibility. It is an application of a bilateral immigration rule. The rule operates whether the applicant is a credible torture victim or a bad-faith applicant. It operated against Pearson not because Canada evaluated his claims and found them wanting but because the United States is officially designated a "safe country" — a designation Pearson correctly identifies as the structural mechanism that makes the program viable. If the country doing the torturing is automatically designated safe, its victims have nowhere to go.

The asylum refusals are not evidence against Pearson's account. They are evidence of the architecture of impunity that surrounds the program he documented.

