## Objection Six: He has no independent witnesses. Everything is his own account.

This objection is factually wrong, and the facts that contradict it are not peripheral. They are central to the evidentiary record.

Lee is a witness. He walked up to Pearson unsolicited and disclosed active surveillance of his apartment. He is not a figure in Pearson's imagination. He sat at an adjacent table and was seen by other people, including the woman who approached Pearson afterward to ask if he knew him. Lee's disclosure is corroborated by the police officers who subsequently responded to words spoken privately in Pearson's home.

Those police officers are witnesses. Their response to Pearson's private in-home speech — arriving and referencing what he said inside his apartment with no active communication device — is documented and is itself the independent confirmation of Lee's disclosure. Two police officers responding to a private remark inside a home is not something that happens by coincidence. It happens because the home is being monitored. The officers are the corroboration.

Ms. Sherry is a witness. She communicated, through the deliberate repetition of a story on a street corner, that she had been shown the contents of Pearson's private telephone conversations. Her disclosure was unprompted and encoded — the behavior of someone making a communication she could not make directly. She is a named individual with a specific relationship to Pearson and a specific incident that is documented.

The librarian is a witness. Not to Pearson's targeting, but to an experience consistent with what the scientific literature describes as thought insertion — an experience the librarian described spontaneously to a coworker in Pearson's presence. The librarian's words are documented. He is a real person with a job at a named institution who said a specific thing that Pearson recorded.

The repair technician who confirmed the neighbor's refrigerator was working is a witness to a specific fact: the refrigerator was functional, meaning the neighbor's stated reason for requesting access to Pearson's home was false.

The psychiatric evaluators who found no pathology are witnesses to the state of Pearson's cognition.

The Congressional record of the MIND Act is a witness to the existence of the technologies Pearson documented.

The Department of War's public statement confirming directed energy weapons is a witness to the existence of the class of weapon Pearson says was deployed against him.

The claim that Pearson has no independent witnesses is not accurate. What is accurate is that he has no witnesses who can testify to the totality of the program — no insider, no co-conspirator, no official document that says "this is the program and this is what we did to Richard Pearson." That absence is not evidence of fabrication. It is evidence of the program's design. Operations of this kind are constructed specifically to prevent the creation of such a document. The absence of a confessing insider is not the same as the absence of corroboration.

