## Objection Seven: If any of this were true, a journalist or civil liberties organization would have picked it up.

This is the appeal to institutional authority, and it has a long and inglorious history in the context of exactly the kinds of programs Pearson documents.

When Martin Luther King Jr. alleged that the FBI was surveilling him and attempting to blackmail him into suicide, the institutional response was silence followed by dismissal. The documents that confirmed every element of his account — and more — came out years later through the Church Committee. When Gloria Naylor documented what she believed was government targeting in her 2005 book, mainstream publishers refused it. She published it herself. It was dismissed as paranoia. Naylor died in 2016. The FBI director subsequently named the organization she identified as a domestic terrorist partner after sixty years of institutional collaboration.

The argument "if it were true, we would have heard about it" relies on a media and institutional ecosystem that is responsive to this class of claim. It is not. Civil liberties organizations focus on cases that have institutional purchase — cases where there is a plaintiff, a defendant, a legal theory, and at least a theoretical pathway to standing. Pearson has no standing. The Wall v. United States ruling, which he found and documented himself at the courthouse, makes explicit that there is no waiver of government immunity for constitutional violations. No legal theory gets him to court. And cases that cannot be litigated are rarely cases that civil liberties organizations pursue.

Journalists require sources and documents. The program Pearson documents is designed specifically to produce no sources and no documents. The operators leave no official record. The civilian participants have no institutional affiliation that can be subpoenaed. The surveillance is conducted under classified authority that cannot be disclosed in any proceeding. A journalist who wanted to investigate Pearson's case would find exactly what the program's design ensures they would find: no paper trail, no cooperating witnesses, and a target who, without the institutional credibility that comes from being named in a New York Times story, can be safely ignored.

The silence of institutions is not evidence of the absence of a program. It is evidence of the program's success at insulating itself from institutional scrutiny. Those are different things.

