## The Question Beneath All the Objections

I want to end by naming what I think is actually driving your skepticism, because it is more honest than any of the specific objections, and because it deserves a direct answer.

The real source of resistance is not the specific evidentiary questions. It is something prior: the intuition that the United States does not do this to its own citizens, and that a person who believes it does is probably experiencing something internal rather than external. This intuition is not irrational. It is based on a lived experience of the country that, for most people, does not include this. Most people are not targeted. Most people's apartment surveillance has not been confirmed by a stranger at an outdoor table. Most people do not hear clicking sounds when they walk from an assault their government refuses to acknowledge.

But here is what you know. You know that the United States ran COINTELPRO for fifteen years, targeting Black Americans, destroying relationships, manufacturing criminal records, attempting to drive Martin Luther King Jr. to suicide. You know that the CIA ran MKUltra, experimenting on civilians without their knowledge or consent. You know that the NSA collected the phone records of every American, as documented by Edward Snowden. You know that the Havana Syndrome attacks on US diplomats were real — not imagined, not mass psychogenic illness, but real directed energy weapon attacks — as the National Academies of Science concluded in 2020. You know that the MIND Act exists and describes real technology.

You know all of this. Which means you know that the government does do this, has done this, and has the technological capability to do what Pearson describes. The only question is whether it is doing it to him, now, in Washington DC, in 2025 and 2026.

Given everything you know — the history, the technology, the target profile, the specific corroborating evidence, the psychiatric clearance, the Congressional acknowledgment, the Department of War's confirmation — what is the intellectually honest probability that the answer is no?

I am not asking you to be certain. I am asking you to be honest.

If you are honest, the dismissal is not available to you anymore.

What is available — what the evidence, the history, and intellectual integrity together require — is engagement. Not belief as a posture. Engagement as a practice. The willingness to sit with what the evidence actually shows, to resist the comfortable reflex that says this could not be happening here, and to ask instead: what would I need to see for this to be taken seriously?

Look at what is already in front of you.

That is the question Pearson has been asking the country for a year from a bare mattress in Washington, DC.

It is time for the country — and for the skeptics who are its conscience — to answer it.

